. Cartwright points to a tension between the idyll (rooted in the national myth of the Jeffersonian yeoman farmer and his idealized family) and the anti-idyll (the aberrant sexuality, gender transgression, and anomalous bodies and minds that are associated with rural white populations). Cartwright examines the anti-idyll in different genres from the 1910s through the 1990s: popular science in the 1910s and early ’20s, documentary photography in the ’30s, news media in the ’50s, poverty tours in the ’60s, horror films in the ’70s and early ’80s, and documentary films in the 1990s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aAmericansxAttitudes. 0aConformityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCountry lifezUnited StatesxPublic opinion. 0aDeviant behaviorzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aamerican studies, united states of america, americanism, rural areas, farmer, farming, population, morality, race, racism, sexuality, sex and gender, 20th century, history, historical research, disability, disabled individuals, gossip, communication, conformity, social expectations, public opinion, attitudes, deviant behavior, photography, poverty, film, horror, identity, documentary.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226697079423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226697079/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles